        "p1": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "LU came home to California with that stone and a question she couldn't let go of: what if the things we dismiss as superstition are just things science hasn't caught up to yet?"
          }
        },
        "p2": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "She started reading about the traditions behind natural stones — not the Instagram version, but the old ones. How cultures across centuries have carried certain stones for protection, clarity, or grounding. Not as magic, but as intention. A quiet ritual of choosing something from the earth and keeping it close."
          }
        },
        "p3": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "As a designer, she saw something else too: natural stones are genuinely, impossibly beautiful. The inclusions, the banding, the irregular shapes — these aren't flaws. They're what happens when nature works without a blueprint."
          }
        }
